To evaluate the sensitivity of proposed sepectrflouorimetric nanosensor and also to investigate minimum detectable concentration of SUM by quenching the system, different concentration of aqueous solution of SUM were added to a solution of DNB-CDs probe in optimized conditions (see Section 2.5). The resulting fluorescence emission spectra of DNB-CDs probe with adding different concentrations of SUM (ranging from 1 to 20 nM) have been illustrated in Fig. 12
                        . The obtained quenching efficiencies were fitted to the Stern-Volmer equation, F0/F = 1 + Ksv[Q], where Ksv is the Stern-Volmer quenching constant, [Q] is the analyte concentration (SUM), and F0 and F are the fluorescence intensity at 380 nm in the absence and presence of SUM, respectively (Fig. 12, inset). As can be seen, the proposed SUM spectroflouorimetric sensor provides a good linear dynamic range (LDR) over the range 1 nM to 15 nM as well as a desired correlation coefficient (R2 = 0.9958). Moreover, the obtained limit of detection (LOD) (0.32 nM or 0.08 ng/mL) based on (3σ/slope) showed a high sensitivity of proposed toward trace amount of SUM. The analytical performance of the proposed spectroflouourimetric procedure based on modified CDs probe has been compared with a reported conventional spectroflouorimeric method and other spectrophotometric methods (Table 1
                        ). As seen, while the LOD of all reported methods are located in the range of μg/L, the LOD of the proposed DNB-CDs based fluorescence method (this work) is in ng/mL category. Moreover, its LDR and RSD values are the same or comparable with other reported methods.

In order to investigate the application of this method for analysis of real samples, the amount of SUM was determined in spiked healthy human urine samples (2–10 nM) and in a pharmaceutical preparation (Migrakim tablet, Hakim Co., Iran). All analytical measurements were performed through standard addition method. The urine samples were diluted ten times with distilled water and filtrated through filter membrane (0.22 μm) before performing the proposed analytical method. The obtained results have been summarized in Table 3
                        . As listed in Table 3, all recoveries were above 90%, verifying satisfactory average recoveries for urine samples with acceptable RSD values. Furthermore, the results obtained from analyzing pharmaceutical sample with the proposed method were satisfactory with average SUM recoveries between 97% and 103% (Table 4
                        ). It must be noted that the whole experiment including sample pretreatment procedure could be completed in 30 min, indicating that the proposed method could address the need for rapid detection of SUM in real samples.
